Thought for 10s

The USDC implementation contract (0x43506849d7c04f9138d1a2050bbf3a0c054402dd) shows very few events/transactions because almost no one interacts with it directly. Why so few events?It is only the logic library, not the actual token contract.
All real USDC activity (billions of transfers, approvals, etc.) happens on the proxy contract (0xa0b86991c6218b36c1d19d4a2e9eb0ce3606eb48).
The proxy uses delegatecall to run the implementation’s code in the proxy’s own storage context. The implementation contract itself rarely receives direct calls.

Direct transactions to the implementation are limited to:Rare upgrades (Circle changing to a new implementation version).
Occasional admin/maintenance calls (e.g., Initialize, specific authorization setups, or direct calls from trusted contracts).
A few mistaken or specialized direct interactions (e.g., some MEV bots or contracts calling it explicitly, though most go through the proxy).

That’s why Etherscan shows only ~140 total transactions ever, with the most recent ones days or weeks old. The proxy, by contrast, has tens of millions of transactions and events. 

etherscan.io

Why do MEV bot calls still appear there?When a bot (or anyone) calls transfer, transferWithAuthorization, approve, etc. on the proxy, Etherscan’s decoder links the executed logic and emitted events back to the implementation because that’s where the function signatures and event definitions live. So you occasionally see MEV-related methods/events surface on the impl page, but only when Etherscan highlights those specific decoded calls.In short: The implementation contract is intentionally “quiet” by design. The real busyness lives on the proxy. This is standard for upgradeable proxy patterns (like Circle’s FiatToken). If you want to see full USDC activity, always look at the proxy address.

